Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:24.340 --> 06:33.940
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy. And here are your hosts.

06:38.640 --> 06:44.540
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. As children, many science fiction and fantasy readers read the Oz books of L. Frank Baum.

06:45.000 --> 06:49.640
Baum wrote 14 novels in the series. After his death, the other authors contributed to the series.

06:49.880 --> 06:55.380
We asked Fred Meyer, president of the International Wizard of Oz Club, to tell us how many other Oz books have been written.

06:56.620 --> 07:08.460
Nowadays there are 40 books in the series, which means there would be 26 in the series after that one. But there are other Oz books besides the ones in the official series.

07:09.480 --> 07:15.520
When we asked Meyer if the Oz books not written by Baum are successful on all levels as Baum's, he allowed that it's a matter of opinion.

07:16.600 --> 07:23.560
Here's where you get into the subjective feelings about them. It's difficult to give a definitive answer on this.

07:24.420 --> 07:34.480
Each author wrote somewhat differently about Oz. As a child, I accepted all of the books and enjoyed them.

07:34.480 --> 07:44.560
But as an adult, I can see differences between the way the authors wrote. There are people who will not read any books except Baum's.

07:45.080 --> 07:49.800
And then there's others that will accept this author, that author, and are choosy that way.

07:50.660 --> 07:56.960
But the authors often wrote just for the children and didn't tend to write on quite so many levels.

07:57.480 --> 08:06.560
Well, there are strange things in the other books by that, I mean on different levels, on the level of meaning and terms of course.

08:07.140 --> 08:11.340
But Baum's seem to be more successful at that than the others were.

08:11.840 --> 08:21.260
Another characteristic of the Oz books, those written by other authors as well as those written by Baum, is the beautiful illustrations by the Imperial Illustrator of Oz, John R. Neill.

08:21.260 --> 08:27.380
Here, Meyer tells us how Neill became the principal illustrator of the series and how later he even wrote some Oz novels.

08:30.000 --> 08:35.000
The publishers asked him to illustrate the second Oz book, and after that, they liked his work and asked him to illustrate the others. 

08:36.000 --> 08:50.000
He was a young artist in Philadelphia at the time and illustrated things there, other books even, but he was just starting his career in 1904 when the second Oz book came out.

08:51.260 --> 08:59.260
He became very closely associated with Oz. Many persons think of the characters as he drew them, rather than as any other artist drew them.

09:00.060 --> 09:03.160
And of course eventually he wrote three books as well as illustrated them.

09:04.500 --> 09:10.640
Between 1944 and 1942 he illustrated all of the Oz books that came out, which is quite a span of years.

09:11.980 --> 09:16.240
Meyer is president of the International Wizard of Oz Club. Here he tells us a bit about it.

09:16.920 --> 09:27.500
Well, the club has at different times, between a thousand, two thousand members, and all kinds of people are in the club.

09:28.380 --> 09:36.480
Very young children, adults of many years are in it, and of all kinds of interesting professions are in it.

09:36.700 --> 09:42.300
But we do have in common some affection for Oz or the creation or idea of it.

09:42.300 --> 09:49.460
Many of us are collecting the books, and many just simply want reading copies. Others want to build fine collections.

09:50.320 --> 09:59.020
Some have other interests, such as the 1939 movie and finding all kinds of memorabilia concerning it.

09:59.600 --> 10:05.460
There's all kinds of ways to go to Oz's collection. But we get together and we talk over the books and what we like best.

10:06.900 --> 10:10.760
We have quizzes over the books. We collect the old films.

10:12.140 --> 10:19.920
L. Frank Baum had an Oz film company in 1915, and we collect some of the films made then, 14-15, a film.

10:20.020 --> 10:24.400
It's silent of course, but interesting to see how he thought an Oz film should be made.

10:25.720 --> 10:29.660
And we do all kinds of things. Sing some of the songs from the stage plays.

10:32.460 --> 10:35.420
Discuss how to identify the different editions.

10:38.240 --> 10:45.320
Well, I just generally just, it's a mutual interest organization, and help each other find the books we need.

10:45.640 --> 10:52.860
So fans of the Oz series, those who never lost their love for it, have a club where they can meet others with the same interests.

10:53.340 --> 10:55.500
We'll look at another Oz related novel on our next show.

