12:38.980 --> 12:40.460
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon.

12:41.000 --> 12:48.000
Many children are exposed through fantasy in the form of Dorothy's adventures in the land of Oz. They're exposed to the books by L. Frank Baum and others and through the famous Judy Garland movie, The Wizard of Oz. 

12:49.760 --> 12:53.380
Most children forget Oz as they grow up, but some continue to love it.

12:53.760 --> 12:56.840
Some of these even become members of the International Wizard of Oz Club.

12:57.520 --> 13:04.320
One man who loved Oz as a child, never forgot it, and even wrote a book featuring Oz is science fiction author Philip Jose Farmer.

13:05.020 --> 13:12.340
1982 saw the release of Farmer's book, A Barnstormer in Oz, and hardcovered by Fantasia Press, and later in a trade paperback edition by Berkley.

13:12.720 --> 13:16.380
Here Farmer tells us about his early love for Oz, and why he wrote a book about it.

13:17.000 --> 13:36.000
I've always had a desire since I was young to be a writer and I've always wanted to write an Oz book. I didn't get around to it until I was 64 years old. Of course, the book I would write when I was 64 is quite different from the one I would write when I was 10 or 11.

13:37.480 --> 13:45.320
 In A Barnstormer in Oz, Farmer writes about Hank Stover, Dorothy's son, who accidentally enters the land of Oz while flying his World War I vintage biplane in the late 1920s.

13:46.300 --> 13:48.220
Farmer told us a bit about the plot of the book.

14:05.340 --> 14:13.460
If you don't assume that only the first Oz book, The Wonderful Wizard of Oz, is true and that all the rest are fiction and none of them approaches Oz from a science fictional viewpoint. If it did, then you have to explain how Scarecrow could be animated and sentient and talk.

14:14.280 --> 14:16.440
What would happen if animals could talk?

14:17.460 --> 14:31.020
How do you account for the Tin Woodman's piecemeal method of being reconstructed out of tin, and explain magic and all that sort of stuff, just where Oz was?

14:31.820 --> 14:45.080
I had a lot of fun doing it, but I also had to do an awful lot of research, because it took place in 1923, and I had to read all about what was happening in America at that time.

14:49.580 --> 15:07.220
I've been a World War I, an early aviation buff, and I have a considerable library on that, but I still had to look up a lot of things on the jettings, and on the machine guns, and the BARs of that period, and Army organization, politics, and all that sort of thing.

15:09.600 --> 15:20.960
Plus, of course, the agonizing task of being able to explain in a rational manner just how the land of Oz could exist, and how all these beings could exist in it.

15:39.180 --> 15:48.900
By claiming that Baum's first book, The Wizard of Oz, is fact, but that the remaining 40 or so books in the series are fiction, Farmer simplified his writing task. He had another reason for doing this, though.

15:50.000 --> 15:56.520
Baum's books had so many changes and contradictions in them later on that it would be impossible to explain.

15:58.280 --> 16:12.140
Plus the fact that if you are writing an original Oz novel, you can do it without getting permission from the people who own the copyright, because the first two books had gone out of copyright.

16:12.140 --> 16:39.420
I ascertained that before I thought seriously about starting to write on them. I wrote to Riley Company in Chicago, and they told me that I could go ahead and write an Oz novel as long as I did not use any new characters or places in the later books.

16:39.420 --> 16:46.420
That is, those that were written after the first two, if they contained new characters, let's say like the hungry tiger.

16:47.480 --> 16:50.500
More on Philip Jose Farmer and Oz on our next show.

