18:30.080 --> 18:31.400
This is Bill Vernon.

18:31.680 --> 18:32.260
And Daryl Lane.

18:32.260 --> 18:37.260
Science Fiction author Philip Jose Farmer recently published an Oz novel called A Barnstormer in Oz.

18:37.760 --> 18:43.200
His premise is that the first book in the Oz series, The Wizard of Oz, is fact, but all the remaining books are fantasy.

18:43.700 --> 18:47.280
We asked Farmer for what audience he was aiming when he wrote A Barnstormer in Oz.

18:49.420 --> 18:50.460
Science fiction audience.

18:52.940 --> 18:58.240
Although, of course, there are a lot of people who don't read much science fiction, they're still like Oz.

19:00.500 --> 19:03.040
But primarily, I think I was writing it for myself.

19:03.440 --> 19:06.760
I mean, you know, you get down to the bottom of it.

19:06.820 --> 19:10.780
Because I've always loved Oz, and I always wanted to write in Oz, but I finally did it.

19:11.540 --> 19:17.480
Readers may be surprised to learn the inspirations for two of the characters, Sharts the Shirtless and Blogo, the Rare Beast.

19:18.600 --> 19:21.740
There's a character in there called Sharts the Shirtless.

19:23.400 --> 19:26.440
And he actually is a sort of a wild Doc Savage.

19:27.980 --> 19:39.120
Yep, if you were acquainted with the first Doc Savage magazine that came out, you will see the shirt is torn to shreds.

19:40.760 --> 19:50.440
And when the 1965 reissues by Bantam came out, the artist, what was his name?

19:51.360 --> 19:54.240
I can't remember it right off, off right hand.

19:54.240 --> 19:57.880
But anyway, he continued that torn shirt motif.

20:00.260 --> 20:05.920
So Sharts the Shirtless is sort of an Ozian takeoff from Doc Savage.

20:06.540 --> 20:18.000
Plus the fact that his companion, the Rare Beast, Blogo, is sort of a takeoff from Doc Savage's apey buddy, Monk Mayfair.

20:20.140 --> 20:25.940
It doesn't matter to the reader whether he knows that or not, but if he does know it, it might add a little extra flavor.

20:51.840 --> 21:00.340
By making A Barnstormer in Oz science fiction, Farmer had to explain in rational terms some of the elements peculiar to Oz, talking animals for instance.

21:01.920 --> 21:10.700
Scarecrow's instead of being set up to scare away the crows are set up there to advertise the fact that there was food growing there for them.

21:12.840 --> 21:15.000
Well that's the only way it could be.

21:15.920 --> 21:22.020
If crows, as the intelligence of human beings, can talk with them, they're not going to be fooled one minute by Scarecrow, right?

21:22.840 --> 21:30.420
But Dorothy had assumed because of her short stay there that scarecrows were up there for the purpose they were set up for on Earth.

21:31.220 --> 21:32.520
Well I figured out otherwise.

21:33.480 --> 21:40.280
In one scene early in the book, the US Army attempts to send an airplane into Oz's airspace, but the plane crashes and the pilot is killed.

21:40.940 --> 21:45.420
The hero, Hank Stover, and the reader, we hasten to add, finds the barbaric burial scene shocking.

21:46.120 --> 21:50.900
It is an unexpected dimension in the seemingly innocuous land of Oz. We asked Farmer about this scene.

21:51.740 --> 22:01.120
Oz is not a manby-pamby land. It's a real inhabited by real people even if they're very short people.

22:04.800 --> 22:18.100
And if you have people who are descended from the ancient Goths who intermingled the Neanderthals originally, then you're not going to have a society quite like the medieval societies of Earth.

22:18.220 --> 22:20.720
There would be a lot of customs that would be different.

22:23.420 --> 22:33.000
And like all societies, even Oz society, has its sinister aspects, its frightening aspects, its alien aspects.

22:34.060 --> 22:35.940
More on Oz on our next show.

